{"cursor":"25439","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{multiple issues|\n\n\n\n}}\n\n\n\n\n Loan sharking may refer to both legal and illegal services.]]\n\nA 'loan shark' is a person or body that offers loans at extremely high interest\nrates. \"loan shark n. A person who lends money at extortionate interest\nrates, usually illegally.\" The Essential Law Dictionary Sphinx Publishing, An\nimprint of Sourcebooks, Inc. By Amy Hackney Blackwell. 2008\n[http://law.academic.ru/12250/loan_shark] [http://definitions.uslegal.com/l/loansharking/ Loansharking\nLaw & Legal Definition] USLegal.com The term usually refers to illegal\nactivity, but may also refer to predatory lending with extremely high interest\nrates such as payday or title loans. [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/borrowing/894016-\n2/Payday-loans-legal-loan-sharking-or-a-better-bet-than-the-banks.html Payday\nloans: legal loan-sharking or a better bet than the banks?] The Telegraph,\nDecember 7, 2011 ''Quick Cash: The Story of the Loan SharkNorthern\nIllinois University Press By Robert Mayer \"Loan sharks may conjure up an image\nof tough guys in fedoras looking to make a profit off of desperate people in\ndire financial straits, but in reality, lenders who advance small sums of cash\nat high interest rates until payday existed long before organized crime entered\nthe trade. Today the businesses that fill this niche in the credit market prefer\nthe name 'payday lenders' rather than loan sharks, but most large cities are\nstill a hotbed of usurious lending, and the landscapes are dotted with their\ninviting and brightly colored storefronts. Despite their more respectable name,\nthese predatory lenders have endured through regulation, prohibition, and the\nrise and fall of the mob since the late 1800s.\" [http://books.google.com/books?-\nid=y52WSQAACAAJ&dq=loan+shark&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mT_mT9G9D4ji2gXcz-\njaCQ&ved=0CEsQ6AEwAg] [http://www.guardian-\nseries.co.uk/news/9529277.WALTHAMSTOW__MP_shocked_by__legal_loan_shark__school_-\ninvolvement/ WALTHAMSTOW: MP shocked by 'legal loan shark' school involvement]\nBy Daniel Binns, [[The Guardian]] Tuesday 14th February 2012 [http://-\nbooks.google.com/books?id=vhJRUGu9s8sC&pg=PA75&dq=legal+loan+shark&hl=en&sa=X&e-\ni=J0rmT8P2McnU2AXji5zaCQ&ved=0CEYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=legal%20loan%20shark&f=fal-\nse Contemporary Financial Intermediation] by By Stuart I. Greenbaum and Anjan V.\nThakor Academic Press 2007 [http://books.google.com/books?id=zoZEKhFC-\n8h8C&pg=PA13&dq=%22legal+loan+shark%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=uknmT6_AM-\nTW2AWv_JzaCQ&ved=0CE8Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22legal%20loan%20shark%22&f=false When\nPayday Loans Go Wrong] By Steve Perry, Pneuma Springs Publishing 2011 [http://www.amazon.co.uk/Loan-Sharks-Rise-Payday-\nLending/dp/1907720545/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1352975486&sr=8-1 Loan Sharks: The\nRise and Rise of Payday Lending] By Carl Packman, Searching Finance 2012\nLoan sharks sometimes enforce repayment by [[blackmail]] or threats of violence.\nHistorically, manymoneylenders'' skirted between legal and extra-legal activity.\nIn the recent western world, loan sharks have been a feature of the criminal\nunderworld.\n","linknr":341,"url":"Loan_shark","recorded":1374521366,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Loan_shark&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Loan_shark&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/loa